Jazz up your holiday ham leftovers with this easy recipe! Take 8 to 10 slices of baked ham and glaze with pineapple juice, brown sugar, and dijon mustard. Bake with tart red cherries and pineapple slices. A sweet and savory dish that pairs perfectly with #MainStBistro Signature Mashed Potatoes.

Instructions:
1. Arrange sliced boneless cooked ham on a baking sheet. 
2. Top with sliced pineapple and cherries. 
3. Make the glaze: Mix 1 tbs pineapple juice, 1 tbs brown sugar, and 1 tbs dijon mustard. 
4. Brush glaze onto ham and bake for 20 minutes until the glaze caramelizes and turns golden brown.

Ornament place card holders to make your table SPARKLE! ✨ These gems are so simple to DYI, you can create the look in the amount of time it takes to heat up your delicious #MainStBistro sides. 🎄

What you'll need: Foam ornament balls, glue, and card stock

Instructions: 
1. Carefully cut the bottom off your foam ornament balls, making them level with the table. 
2. Cut the card stock to fit the ornament size, then write your guest's name. 
3. Glue the cut card stock onto the ornament's top hook and let dry.

Mulled Cider is a warming winter beverage, perfect for sipping on as you trim the tree or prep dinner with family and friends! Ready to get into the holiday spirit with #MainStBistro?🎄❄️🎁 Here's what you'll need:

- 1 gallon apple cider
- Mulling spices: 2 cinnamon sticks, 1tsp whole cloves, 4 whole star anise, 6 cardamom pods, fresh ginger
- ¼ cup brown sugar
- Orange slices, cinnamon sticks, and whipped cream for serving

1. Combine the apple cider, brown sugar, and mulling spices in a Dutch oven or large pot.
2. Bring to a low simmer over medium heat. Do not let boil. Stir occasionally in the first 10 minutes, or until the brown sugar dissolves. Simmer on low for 30 minutes or up to 2 hours. Strain if desired.
3. Ladle the warm cider into mugs and garnish with a fresh orange slice, cinnamon stick, and/or fresh whipped cream 😋 Enjoy!

Apple, spice, and everything nice... that's what this Caramel Apple Mocktail is made of. 🍎 

Ready to make your own? Here's what you'll need:
- 6 cups apple cider
- 1/2 cup caramel syrup
- 3 cups sparkling water
- 2 tsp cinnamon
- 2 apples
- Rosemary sprigs (around 6)
- Golden brown sugar for rimming

1. Start by making the base of the drink by mixing apple cider, caramel syrup, cinnamon, and cut-up apples. Add the rosemary springs and let sit for 20 minutes.
2. Prep your glasses with a brown sugar rim by preparing two saucers; one with water and one with brown sugar. Rotate the glass in the saucer with water making sure only the outside of the rim gets wet, then roll the glass in the brown sugar and let dry.
3. After 20 minute has passed, pour the sparkling water into the pitcher and mix.
4. Now your drink is ready to be served. Pour the Caramel Apple Pie Mocktail into brown sugar-rimmed glasses with an apple to garnish and enjoy. A drink perfect for the whole family to kick off the Thanksgiving festivities before they start in on the delicious #MainStBistro side dishes!!

Warm up the room with this ambient autumn-colored DIY Leaf Candle Holder, and elevate your holiday entertaining. 🍂

What you'll need: Faux non-waxed leaves, Mod Podge, sponge brush, glass or mason jar

1. Find yourself some fake fall leaves — the thinner the better. You can even carefully peel the leaf "vein" off the back of the leaf to flatten it down.
2. Make sure to wash your glass or jar thoroughly to remove any residual oils. 
3. Spread the Mod Podge on the outside of the glass with a sponge brush, let it dry for a few minutes until it becomes tacky, then carefully press the leaf onto the glue. Let dry for 30 minutes. 
4. Add your final layer of Mod Podge over the glued leaves. This layer will need to dry overnight. By morning, you'll have candle holders fit for a Thanksgiving celebration.

DIY your heart out with this simple yet elegant Dried Orange Place Card. It brings a nice pop of fall color to the Thanksgiving table, while also adding a personalized feel. 

What You'll Need: Vellum paper, permanent marker, dried flowers (gypsum, bunny tails, nigella), ribbon, and dried orange slices

1. Begin by drying your navel oranges. Cut the orange into 1/4" slices and place on a metal cooling rack over a baking sheet. 
2. Bake at 150F degrees for 3 hours, rotating every 30 minutes. 
3. Cut the vellum paper into 1" x 5" pieces. Write each guest's name on a card with the permanent pen. Then punch a hole into the corner of the vellum paper.
4. Assemble the place cards. Poke a hole in the top of the orange slice and thread a ribbon through the hole. This ribbon will be used to secure the dried flowers (gypsum, bunny tail, and nigella) and vellum paper together. And voilà! You've created a nice addition to the dining room table that will make each guest feel supremely special.
